“The sea is ours”: Bolivia, blocked, hopes the court will reopen the way to the Pacific
Marines patrol an armored boat in the naval headquarters of La Paz.
Public buildings bear a blue flag like the ocean.
From Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, the naval bases display the following motorcycle: “The sea is ours.
Getting it back is a duty.”
Throughout blockaded Bolivia, the memory of a coast lost to Chile during a bloody resource conflict in the 19th century is still well-present, as is the desire to sail the Pacific Ocean once again.
Bolivia is awaiting a decision by the International Court of Justice, which will be delivered on 1 October, after five years of deliberations.
“Bolivia has the will, the spirit of unity and serenity, and of course expects a positive result,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will follow the decision of the International Court of Justice on the big screen across the country, hoping that the court in The Hague will rule in favor of the Bolivian request. Bolivia hopes that, after decades of sporadic negotiations, Chile will be obliged to negotiate the agreement of a sovereign passage to the ocean.
Evo Morales, the charismatic indigenous president of Bolivia (who faces a controversial fight for re-election next year), also has a lot to say about the decision that will be made on Monday.
“We are so close to being able to return to the Pacific Ocean,” he said at the end of August.
But some analysts think that there is little chance that the court will rule in favor of Chile, and that little would change, even if a positive decision was made.
The UN body based in the Netherlands does not have the power to grant Chilean territory, and stipulated that it would not determine the outcome of any talks.
The fact that the International Court of Justice renders its decision six months after the last arguments shows that the case “was not complicated,” explains Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
And far from favoring the cause of Bolivia, the last four years may even have hurt it.
“The problem of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration,” Zárate said.
Morales’ belligerent rhetoric undermined all the remaining Chilean goodwill, she suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will continue to exchange, but after that, it will be very difficult to hold talks.
The last exchange of ambassadors between the two countries took place in 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltze, who represents Bolivia in The Hague, rejected the idea that the Court’s decision was abnormally fast.
On Monday, it will bring Bolivia “an extraordinary opportunity to start a new era of relations with Chile” and a chance to “end 139 years of disagreement with mutual benefits,” he said.
Calzadilla also disputed the fact that Morales - who remains to this day one of the most popular presidents of Latin America - used the maritime problem as a political crutch.
“Bolivia will never give up its right of access to the Pacific Ocean,” he added.
“The Court’s decision is an opportunity to see that we have to get rid of the past.”
