North Korea says that disarmament can in no case be done unilaterally without confidence.
On Saturday, the North Korean foreign minister told the United Nations that maintaining sanctions was strengthening his mistrust of the United States and that it would be impossible for his country to unilaterally renounce its nuclear weapons in these circumstances.
At the World Organization’s Annual General Assembly, Ri Yong Ho said North Korea had taken “important measures of goodwill” last year, such as ending nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site, and its commitment not to proliferate nuclear weapons and technology.
"However, we do not see any corresponding response from the United States," he said.
In the absence of confidence in the United States, we will fear for our national security and, under such circumstances, it is excluded that we are the first to disarm unilaterally.”
While reiterating North Korea's well-known accusations of Washington's opposition to a "step-by-step" approach to denuclearization under which North Korea would be rewarded if it took steps gradually, its statement proved important in that it did not reject the idea of a past denuclearization.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump, made on June 12 in Singapore at the very first summit between a US president in office and a North Korean leader, when Kim pledged to work for a “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula” while Trump promised North Korea’s security.
North Korea seeks to officially end the Korean War (1950-1953), but the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also rejected demands for easing tough international sanctions against North Korea.
The United States insists that North Korea first proceed with denuclearization and accentuate the pressure by imposing sanctions to achieve their goal in a coercive manner, even opposing the "end of war declaration."
“Those who think that these sanctions can make us rain don’t know us.
The problem is that maintaining sanctions increases our mistrust.”
Ri made no comment on the second summit between Kim and Trump highlighted before the United Nations by the U.S. leader earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings that took place between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the party concerned with the issue of denuclearization was South Korea and not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be in such a state.”
Nevertheless, Ri’s tone of speech was radically different from last year’s, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to point North Korean missiles at North American territory after “evil” President Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea before the United Nations, did not laud this year for the courage with which Kim applied measures for disarmament, but added that much remains to be done and that sanctions would not be lifted until North Korea does.
On Wednesday, Trump said no deadline had been set. “It can take two years, three years or five months; it doesn’t matter,” he said.
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the United Nations Security Council on Thursday: “The implementation of the Security Council sanctions must be firmly and systematically maintained until total, definitive and verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously strengthened sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to stifle funding for Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and then announced that he would return to Pyongyang next month to prepare for a second summit.
This year, Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times, but his last trip was somewhat disastrous.
In July, he left Pyongyang claiming that progress had been made but, in the hours that followed, North Korea denounced its “gangster methods.”
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile site as well as a nuclear complex if the United States took “equivalent measures.”
According to the South Korean president, Kim is demanding security assurances promised by Trump in Singapore, and efforts to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard: Students Take Rest Lessons
This year, Harvard University has put in place a new course that allows all undergraduate students to sleep more and fights the growing macho trend of studying by consuming caffeine all night long.
One professor noted that most students at the best university in the world do not know how to take care of them
This course, designed by Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is according to him the first of its kind in the United States.
It was after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning that the idea came to him.
In the end, a student approached me and said, “Why is this only being told to me in the last year?”
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
Delivered for the first time this year, this course explains to students the need to adopt good sleep habits to improve their school and physical performance, as well as their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and general director of the university’s health services, said the university had decided to introduce the course after finding students suffering from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The course time consists of various interactive exercises.
One of the sections presents the image of a dormitory containing different objects (coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, books...) on which students click to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on their physical performance and the importance of integrating a routine.
In another section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons then invites participants to reflect on their daily routine.
“We know that this will not instantly change the behavior of students.
However, in our opinion, they have the right to know this information – just as you have the right to know what the health effects of smoking are,” added Professor Czeisler.
According to him, the culture of pride in “passing a white night” still exists, and he adds that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students make sleep deprivation a growing problem.
Having enough and good quality sleep should be students' "secret weapon" to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said - even to avoid gaining weight, as lack of sleep puts the brain in a state of starvation, making them hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old chemistry and physical biology student from California, helped Professor Czeisler design this course after being one of his students last year during his first year at Harvard.
He claimed that this course had opened his eyes and prompted him to insist that it be offered throughout the campus.
He hopes that the next step will be to offer all postgraduate students a similar degree program before joining the reputable institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends students to provide an alarm for both bedtime and waking time, and to be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED light, which can disrupt their circadian rhythm and lead to sleep disorders.
