The National Trust monitors the secret life of bats
New research in a Scottish Highlands area seeks to reveal how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
It is hoped that the observations will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and guide future conservation activities.
The National Trust for Scotland researchers will follow common bats and sopranos as well as long-eared brown bats and Daubenton at Inverewe Garden in Wester Ross.
Special check-in devices will be placed at key locations around the property to monitor bat activities throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using portable detectors.
A professional sound analysis will determine the frequency of bat screams as well as the activities of the different species.
A map and habitat report will be drawn up to provide a detailed picture of their behaviour across the territory.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor for the NTS, hopes that the results will reveal the most important habitat areas for bats and how they are used by each of these species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work such as grassland creation and the best way to preserve forests for bats and other related species.
In Scotland and the United Kingdom, bat populations have declined considerably over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects the perch and results in the loss of their habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, just like fly-kill papers and certain chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks from pet cats.
The bats are not really blind.
However, given their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to spot insects and obstacles on their flight route.
Responsible for the protection of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, the NTS takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who regularly carry out surveys, perch inspections and sometimes rescues.
The organization also established the first and only stock of Scottish bats at the Threave site in Dumfries-et-Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
David Thompson, the domain manager, says the site is the ideal territory for them.
“Here at Threave, we have an ideal place for bats,” he says.
“We have old buildings, lots of old trees and all the right habitat.
But there’s still a lot to learn about bats, so the work we’re doing here and elsewhere will help us better understand what bats need to thrive.”
He stressed the importance of verifying the presence of bats before proceeding with the maintenance of the properties, because by destroying without it a single maternity nest, it can cause the death of 400 females and small ones, or even the disappearance of an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, disturb them, or destroy their perch.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
“We still have a lot to learn about our bats and as far as many of our species are concerned, we don’t know what’s going on in their populations right now.”
