Red tide info point: Decreased concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fisheries and Wildlife Commission indicates a general decrease in red tide concentrations in some areas of the Tampa Bay region.
According to the CPF, more irregular flowering conditions are reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte, and Collier counties – which raise fears of declining concentrations.
The red tide covers about 209 km (130 miles) of coastline, from the north of Pinellas to the south of Lee County.
There are islets about 16 km (10 miles) off Hillsborough County, but in fewer locations than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Moderate concentrations in or off Pinellas County were reported last week, low to high concentrations off Hillsborough County, higher concentrations in Manatee County, higher concentrations at the bottom of Sarasota County or off, average concentrations at the bottom of Charlotte County, high or low concentrations at the bottom of Charlotte County and high or low concentrations at the bottom of Charlotte County.
Cases of respiratory irritation persist in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation has been reported in northwest Florida over the past week.
